Integer and Float Wrapper Class Caching in Java
1. Integer Caching Concept**

In Java, the `Integer` wrapper class uses a caching mechanism for better performance and memory optimization.

Java caches `Integer` objects in the range -128 to 127. When values within this range are assigned, both variables refer to the same object in memory.

Integer a = -128;
Integer b = -128;
System.out.println(a == b); // true

In this case, `a` and `b` refer to the same cached object, so `==` returns `true`.
However, values outside this range are not cached:


Integer a = 128;
Integer b = 128;
System.out.println(a == b); // false

Here, two separate objects are created, so `==` returns `false` because it compares memory references.

2. Float (and Double) Behavior
Unlike `Integer`, the `Float` wrapper class does not use caching.
Float a = -127.5f;
Float b = -127.5f;
System.out.println(a == b); // false

Even though the values are the same, `a` and `b` refer to different objects, so `==` returns `false`.

3. Why Float Does Not Use Caching

There are several reasons why `Float` and `Double` do not use caching:
* Large Range of Values
* Precision Issues
* Low Reusability
* Memory Inefficiency

4. Important Note on Comparison

* == compares memory references for objects.
* .equals() compares actual values.

Correct way to compare:
System.out.println(a.equals(b)); //true

* Integer uses caching for values between -128 and 127, improving performance and memory usage.
* Float and Double do not use caching due to their large range, precision limitations, and inefficiency in reuse.
* Always use .equals() for comparing wrapper class values instead of ==.
